The theorem has been demonstrated in more physical situation.

Note. 
In this paper, the theorem is shown by a test function with 
a compact support including the light cone in a momentum space
as in Coleman's proof. This corresponds to setting a test state
extended over the whole space-time.
To prove the theorem with a test state
on a space-like surface as in
the famous Mermin-Wagner theorem, 
Bogoliubov's inequality is no use at zero temperature. 
One can use more complicated Shastry's inequality, which was
employed to prove no antiferromagnetic order
in the antiferromagnetic quantum Heisenberg chain. 
This inequality 
works with a test function , 
where the -independence implies no support compactness
and a test state on a space-like surface. 
In this case, one needs the lemma 
under a relaxed condition on  
when the bound by  is available only in some 
neighborhood of the origin.
This version of lemma 
allows one to prove the theorem with the 
test state on a space-like surface.
